## Cargo workspace rules

### Mock workspace

- All hilavitkutin crates use `version.workspace = true`,
  `edition.workspace = true`, `license.workspace = true`.
- Sibling dependencies use `.workspace = true` syntax.
- External dependencies declared in `[workspace.dependencies]`.
- Edition 2024 for all crates.

### Crate structure

Seven crates today, flat — all plain `rlib`, no proc-macro crates.
(Eighth crate `hilavitkutin-plugins` lands in a follow-up round.)

- `hilavitkutin-api` — consumer-facing contracts. Traits and data
  shapes only; no concrete engine logic.
- `hilavitkutin` — the engine. Depends on `hilavitkutin-api` and
  on arvo substrate crates.
- `hilavitkutin-build` — **build-dep only**. Declared under
  `[build-dependencies]` in the consumer, never under
  `[dependencies]`. No runtime linkage.
- `hilavitkutin-ctx`, `hilavitkutin-persistence`, `hilavitkutin-str`
  — standalone extensions. Each is independently usable. They do
  not depend on the engine, on `hilavitkutin-api`, or on each other.
- `hilavitkutin-extensions` — plugin-host layer: cross-platform
  dynamic library loader primitive. `no_std`, no allocator.
  Provides abstractions that downstream consumer hosts (viola,
  loimu, etc.) use to load their own cdylib plugins. Depends
  only on notko / arvo / arvo-bits substrate and on libc /
  windows-sys for raw FFI. Must never depend on
  `hilavitkutin-api` or `hilavitkutin`.

### Plugin host crates (layer, not loophole)

`hilavitkutin-extensions` is itself a plain `rlib`. It provides
abstractions for loading cdylib plugins; it is not a cdylib target
itself. No hilavitkutin crate is a cdylib target — the dynamic
`cdylib` ecosystems exist only downstream of this layer, in the
consumer hosts that use it.

The upcoming `hilavitkutin-plugins` crate (separate design round)
will sit above `hilavitkutin-extensions` and provide plugin
descriptor registration, lifecycle orchestration, and role/capability
dispatch — still domain-agnostic, still a plain `rlib`. Domain-
specific contract crates (viola-plugin-abi, etc.) layer further on
top in consumer repos.

This layering is deliberate. The engine stays at strict static
composition; downstream consumers get a reusable plugin-host
foundation without every consumer rewriting raw dlopen.

### Dependency direction

- `hilavitkutin-api`: no hilavitkutin crate deps. May depend on
  arvo substrate if it needs numeric types. Must never depend on
  `hilavitkutin` (circular).
- `hilavitkutin` → `hilavitkutin-api` + arvo substrate crates.
- `hilavitkutin-build`: zero hilavitkutin crate deps; may depend on
  LLVM / cargo / rustc toolchain crates. Strictly build-time.
- `hilavitkutin-ctx`, `-persistence`, `-str`: independent. Each
  may depend on arvo substrate; none depend on the engine or on
  each other.
- `hilavitkutin-extensions`: depends only on notko / arvo / arvo-bits
  substrate and on libc (unix) / windows-sys (windows) for raw FFI.
  Must never depend on `hilavitkutin-api`, `hilavitkutin`, or any
  other hilavitkutin crate.

### `no_std` + `no_alloc` enforcement

Every crate's `lib.rs` starts with:

```rust
#![no_std]
#![deny(unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn)]
// no `extern crate alloc;`
```

`Cargo.toml` must not pull `std`-feature variants of any dependency.
If an arvo crate exposes a `std` feature, it stays off.

### ExpandedLto pragma

`hilavitkutin-build` provides the `ExpandedLto` pragma (domain 03
in the consolidation topic). The consumer's release profile must
opt into it. This requirement is documented in
`hilavitkutin-build`'s DESIGN doc; lint enforcement comes later
when the pragma's concrete shape lands.

### Substrate (arvo)

Arvo crates are git dependencies on the workspace dev branch for
now. When both projects stabilise, they become versioned crates.io
releases.

```toml
[workspace.dependencies]
arvo          = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-bits     = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-bitmask  = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-graph    = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-sparse   = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-spectral = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-comb     = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
```

When iterating on changes crossing the arvo / hilavitkutin
boundary, add a local `[patch]` temporarily — remove before
pushing.

### Forbidden crate types

- No `[lib] proc-macro = true` in any hilavitkutin crate.
- No `crate-type = ["cdylib"]` on any hilavitkutin crate. The engine
  composes statically; the plugin-host layer
  (`hilavitkutin-extensions`, and later `hilavitkutin-plugins`)
  LOADS cdylibs but is not itself a cdylib target.
- No linker-magic discovery in any hilavitkutin crate. `inventory`,
  `ctor`, `#[distributed_slice]`, `.init_array`-based registration
  are banned on both the producer and consumer sides of the loader
  boundary. `hilavitkutin-extensions` enforces pull-based explicit-
  symbol resolution only.
- No runtime WU discovery in the engine. The engine's WorkUnit
  composition is strictly static. This constraint does not extend
  to consumer hosts' plugin ecosystems, which route through the
  plugin-host layer.
